  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"Do organisms need an impact factor?\" explores the usage patterns and impact of key biological resources and model organisms. Supported by institutions such as Cincinnati Children's Hospital Medical Center and the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School, the research reflects a firm commitment to reproducibility, evidenced by the inclusion of 27 Research Resource Identifiers (RRIDs).</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In \"Do organisms need an impact factor?\", authors Agata Pi\u0119kniewska and colleagues delve into the citation patterns of pivotal biological resources, including model organisms. This examination not only contributes to academic discourse but also underscores the significance of informed usage in biological research. Funded by several NIH agencies, including the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), this work is validated by robust institutional support, particularly from esteemed organizations such as the University of California, San Diego, and the University of Kentucky.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">A notable aspect of this research is the inclusion of 27 Research Resource Identifiers (RRIDs), highlighting a strong commitment to technical reproducibility. These identifiers allow researchers to trace back to the original resources, ensuring that findings can be replicated and validated in future studies. The rigorous attention to reproducibility reflects an essential trend in scientific research, emphasizing the need for transparent and accountable methodologies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the article has yet to attract citations or online mentions, its implications for the research community remain significant. By focusing on how model organisms and key biological resources are cited and utilized, the authors provide insights that could influence future research practices in the field. This foundational research output serves as a conceptual framework for understanding biological resource utilization, which may guide researchers in the design and interpretation of future experiments.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the scientific community continues to grapple with the importance of impact factors and their implications for research funding and resource allocation, this study offers a timely and critical perspective. The absence of existing metrics in the form of citations and mentions underscores the nascent stage of this research within broader discourse, which may evolve as the work gains visibility in academic circles and represents a passionate inquiry into the relationship between scholarly metrics and biological resource usage.</p>",
